Design a principled methodology for combining multiple independent code quality metrics into a single composite quality score for a software file or module. The metrics available are: cyclomatic complexity (per function, aggregated to file level), cognitive complexity (per function, aggregated), maintainability index (per file, 0-100), code duplication percentage, technical debt hours, type annotation coverage percentage (0-100), documentation coverage percentage (0-100), code smell count (weighted by severity), bug pattern count (weighted by severity), and lines of code. The fundamental problem is that these metrics have different scales, different distributions across real codebases, different relationships to actual quality outcomes, and different levels of empirical validation. Some are highly correlated with each other (complexity and maintainability index both depend on LOC), which means naive summation double-counts certain dimensions.

Reason through the following design decisions carefully. First, should the composite score be an arithmetic weighted mean, a geometric mean, a worst-case (min) function, or a hierarchical model where certain categories must pass thresholds before others contribute? Second, how should weights be set — by expert opinion, by empirical correlation with defect density, by principal component analysis to de-correlate the inputs, or by asking developers to rank the importance of each dimension? Third, how should the score handle the case where a file has excellent scores on all metrics except one catastrophic outlier — should a single blocker-severity issue be able to drive the composite score to zero? Fourth, how should the score normalize for file size, since a 2000-line file will naturally have worse absolute metric values than a 50-line file even if both are equally well-written? Fifth, how should the composite score be presented to developers to maximize actionability — as a single number, a letter grade, a radar chart, or a decomposed breakdown by category? Derive concrete recommendations with mathematical formulations where possible.
